// ﻿Technical Sheet: Fusion Runtime Core
// Artifact ID: FUS-003-TECH
// Version: v0.3.0 (Alpha)
// Date: 2025-11-23
// 
// 
// 1. System Requirements
// Fusion Runtime Core is designed for high-performance bare-metal environments. While it can run in containers, performance guarantees (latency/jitter) are only valid on qualified hardware.
// 1.1 Compute (Classical)
// Component
// 	Minimum Specification
// 	Recommended (Production / HFT)
// 	CPU Architecture
// 	x86_64 (AVX2 required)
// 	x86_64 (AVX-512 required) or ARM64 (NEON)
// 	Core Count
// 	4 Physical Cores
// 	16+ Physical Cores (Isolated)
// 	Clock Speed
// 	2.5 GHz+
// 	4.0 GHz+ (Performance Governor enabled)
// 	RAM
// 	16 GB DDR4
// 	128 GB+ DDR5 (ECC preferred)
// 	Page Size
// 	Standard (4KB)
// 	Huge Pages (1GB) enabled
// 	1.2 Accelerator Support (GPU/TPU)
// The runtime uses the fusion_hal crate to interface with accelerators.
// * NVIDIA:
//    * Driver: 525.x or higher.
//    * Architecture: Volta (V100), Ampere (A100/A30), Hopper (H100), Blackwell (B200).
//    * Capabilities: Compute Capability 7.0+.
// * AMD:
//    * Driver: ROCm 5.4+.
//    * Architecture: CDNA2 (MI200 series).
// * TPU:
//    * Support: Coral Edge TPU (Local) or Google Cloud TPU v4 (via gRPC bridge).
// 1.3 Quantum Backend Compatibility
// Fusion v0.3.0 supports the following Quantum Processing Unit (QPU) interfaces via the QEM Layer:
// Provider
// 	Interface
// 	Min Qubits
// 	Supported Gateset
// 	IBM Quantum
// 	Qiskit Runtime API
// 	5
// 	Basis: CX, ID, RZ, SX, X
// 	Rigetti
// 	Quil / QCS
// 	8
// 	Native Rigetti
// 	IonQ
// 	API v2
// 	11
// 	Fully Connected (Trapped Ion)
// 	Fusion Sim
// 	CPU-Local
// 	1
// 	Universal Simulator (Clifford+T)
// 	________________
// 2. Software & Kernel Constraints
// To achieve sub-10μs latency, the OS kernel must be tuned significantly.
// 2.1 Operating System
// * Supported: RHEL 9, Ubuntu 22.04 LTS, Debian 12.
// * Kernel: Linux 5.15+ generic (Minimum), Linux 6.1+ PREEMPT_RT (Recommended for HFT).
// 2.2 Kernel Parameters (sysctl)
// For production deployment, the following boot parameters are required to isolate the runtime from OS noise:
// 
// 
// Bash
// 
// 
// 
// 
// # /etc/default/grub
// GRUB_CMDLINE_LINUX="isolcpus=4-15 nohz_full=4-15 rcu_nocbs=4-15 hugepagesz=1G hugepages=16 default_hugepagesz=1G intel_iommu=on"
// 
// * isolcpus: Prevents the OS scheduler from interrupting Fusion worker threads.
// * nohz_full: Disables the scheduler tick on pinned cores.
// * intel_iommu=on: Enables userspace driver access (VFIO) for zero-copy networking.
// 2.3 Dependencies
// * Rust Toolchain: Nightly-2025-10-01 (or later).
// * System Libs: libnuma-dev, libssl-dev, pkg-config.
// * Python: Python 3.10+ (Required only if using Qiskit/Cirq bindings).
// ________________
// 3. Network Specifications (HFT Module)
// If the fusion_finance crate is active, specific network hardware is required for kernel bypass.
// * NIC Support:
//    * Mellanox ConnectX-5, ConnectX-6 (Dx/Lx).
//    * Solarflare X2522.
//    * Intel X710/XL710.
// * Driver Stack: DPDK 22.11 LTS.
// * Protocol Support:
//    * TCP/IP (User-space stack, zero-copy).
//    * UDP Multicast (IGMP v3).
//    * FIX 4.2 / 4.4 / 5.0 (Native Parsing).
// ________________
// 4. Performance Limits & Capacity
// Metric
// 	Limit (v0.3.0)
// 	Notes
// 	Max Concurrent Tasks
// 	1,000,000
// 	Soft limit, bounded by RAM.
// 	Max Qubits (Sim)
// 	32
// 	Memory exponential growth ($2^N$).
// 	Event Loop Latency
// 	< 400ns
// 	On pinned cores.
// 	Cold Start Time
// 	< 50ms
// 	JIT compilation overhead excluded.
// 	Throughput (HTTP)
// 	4M Req/sec
// 	Single node, 64 cores.
// 	________________
